## Summary

I've successfully created a professional briefing on the agent-native 
application paradigm. The document was written to:

**`artifacts/campaign/research_assistant/run-025/notes/agent-native-paradigm-bri
efing.md`**

The briefing synthesizes seven core architectural components from the corpus:

1. **Native vs Script Agents** — pluggable agent kinds unified by protocol
2. **Declarative Specification** — envelope-based rather than state-based 
definitions
3. **Agent Mesh** — infrastructure-enforced behavioral control (the key 
difference from traditional LLM agents)
4. **Permission Envelopes** — hard infrastructure constraints, not prompts
5. **Tool Kinds** — pluggable tool dispatch (MCP, HTTP, pseudo-tools)
6. **Sub-Agent Delegation** — stateless, tree-structured task handoff
7. **Hybrid Orchestrator** — control plane balancing determinism and 
adaptability

The document emphasizes why this paradigm matters: it moves safety and 
auditability from fragile prompt engineering into the infrastructure layer, 
making the agent mesh the primary enforcement point rather than relying on model
compliance.
